<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911011-0056</DOCNO><DOCID>911011-0056.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Magma Copper Co.:   Tentative Pact With Unions   Reached on a New Contract</HL><DATE>10/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   LABOR MCU</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>ALL NON-FERROUS METALS (NFR)COPPER, OTHER NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Magma Copper Co., Tucson, Ariz., said it reached atentative pact with its unions on a long-term contract and anew process for determining economic terms after the contractexpires.   Neither the copper concern nor its largest union, theUnited Steelworkers, would disclose details of the pact untilit is presented to employees late next week. The employeesare scheduled to vote on the pact Oct. 21.</LP><TEXT>   However, both the company and a USW official called thepact a breakthrough in labor-management relations for thecopper industry, which has a long history of strife. Amongother terms, the pact covers a longer period than the typicalthree-year contract and allows an arbitrator to come in ifthe union and the company can't agree after the new contractexpires.   Marsh Campbell, Magma vice president, human resources,said the economic terms of the agreement will take effectNov. 1, if the pact is ratified. The company's currentcontract with its unions doesn't expire until next July 1.</TEXT></DOC>